      "summary": "Culture Shock at UCT  \r\nBy Mohammed Kajee, Dale Taylor, Olerato Mogomotsi, Forgiveness Jofana, Thabo Maliea, Tsatsawani Mnisi, Denzel Mtoko & Akha Tutu\r\n\r\nUkukhula kukubona izinto. To grow is to see things. (One grows through experience.) – isiXhosa proverb\r\n\r\nScience is Tough (But So Are You!)\r\n\r\nWelcome to UCT! Coming to UCT often means entering a completely new cultural and social environment, which may be different from what you’re used to. You might find that UCT is very different from your school, is far from your family, friends, and support system, is in a new city or country, forces you to interact with unfamiliar cultures, accents, and food, and is highly competitive.\r\n\r\nThis new environment can evoke a mix of emotions, including excitement and discomfort, which may be culture shock. This chapter aims to help you understand and manage your experience at UCT, and if you aren’t facing these challenges, it can help you better understand those who are.\r\n\r\nWhile it’s important to celebrate your achievement of being accepted into UCT, it’s also essential to reflect on how UCT’s culture impacts students. This chapter briefly explores culture, culture shock, identity crisis, and imposter phenomenon to help you navigate the UCT environment successfully.\r\n\r\nWhat Is Culture Anyway?\r\n\r\nCulture is like water – we can be so immersed in it that we can’t see it. Culture is present in our customs, traditions, and daily routines. Although it helps us function in society, it often advantages some people at the expense of others.\r\n\r\nSouth Africa’s Constitution aims to build a society based on democratic values and human rights. Despite this, many aspects of South African society have been shaped by Western and capitalist cultural norms, which are competitive and consumerist. We should critically assess whether this dominant culture aligns with our values.\r\n\r\nAt UCT, your plans can be altered as you’re exposed to a much larger world. UCT’s institutional culture is shaped by its history, which began in 1829 as a high school for white male students. Black students were only admitted in the 1920s, and their numbers remained small until the 1980s.\r\n\r\nThe 2015 ‘Rhodes Must Fall’ protests brought attention to the impact of UCT’s culture on Black students. UCT responded by creating the Institutional Reconciliation and Transformation Commission (IRTC), which found that racism exists at UCT and manifests as subtle micro-aggressions. Many students described the university’s systems as colonial, white-supremacist, patriarchal, and anti-poor. UCT leadership is committed to transforming its institutional culture to be more inclusive and equitable through Vision 2030, which aims to create a fair and just society.\r\n\r\nExperiencing Culture Shock at UCT\r\n\r\nMany science students experience culture shock at UCT. This can stem from moving to a new environment where the norms and laws may differ from what they’re used to. University students often adapt to some extent, but assimilation doesn’t mean abandoning your beliefs. Below are stories of students who faced culture shock and how they navigated their new environment.\r\n\r\nMy Story: Feeling Out of Place in the World  \r\nA UCT BSc student shares their experience of moving to different African countries throughout their life, which made them feel out of place. When they first came to UCT, they were frightened and worried about fitting in. However, they have since adjusted and are falling in love with Cape Town.\r\n\r\nMy Story: I Have Faith in My Culture  \r\nForgiveness Jofana, a UCT BCom student from Zimbabwe, reflects on how their cultural upbringing made it difficult to adjust to UCT’s environment. In Zimbabwe, certain dress codes and beliefs are important, and adjusting to UCT’s more progressive atmosphere was challenging. However, they continue to hold faith in their culture.\r\n\r\nMy Story: Navigating Cultural Differences  \r\nDenzel Mtoko, a third-year BBusSc student, describes the difficulty of adjusting to UCT’s inclusive culture, especially regarding LGBTQ+ acceptance. In their home country, homosexuality is legally prohibited and culturally frowned upon, making the transition to UCT’s more progressive environment complex.",
