      "category": "Mental Health",
      "summary": "how does your brain work?\r\n\r\nnew neural pathways\r\nYour brain builds new pathways between neurons by connecting new knowledge to existing knowledge. Active mental engagement, such as practicing skills or creating mind maps, is essential for learning. Watching or reading about a skill without practicing it does not build the necessary neural pathways for effective learning.\r\n\r\nforgetting curve and spaced repetition\r\nThe forgetting curve shows that people forget information over time, retaining only about 25% by the end of a week. Spaced repetition, which involves regularly reviewing material, interrupts the forgetting curve and helps retain information more effectively. This method is particularly important for learning hierarchical subjects like science.\r\n\r\nlong-term and working memory: recognition versus retrieval\r\nLong-term memory stores information for retrieval, but retrieving information in tests can be challenging. Working memory is limited and can handle only a few things at once. Using strategies like note-taking can help manage this limitation.\r\n\r\ndiffuse versus focused thinking\r\nFocused thinking involves intense concentration on a task, while diffuse thinking occurs when your mind wanders freely. Both modes are valuable: focused thinking helps with specific tasks, and diffuse thinking can lead to creative solutions. The Pomodoro Technique, which alternates focused study with short breaks, can enhance learning.\r\n\r\nneurodiversity\r\nNeurodiversity refers to the variations in how different brains function. Each person’s brain works slightly differently, influencing their perception and cognitive processes. This diversity means that learning strategies that work for one person may not work for another.\r\n\r\nthe vital role of sleep in learning\r\nSleep is crucial for learning as it helps consolidate memories and maintain brain health. REM sleep consolidates what you’ve learned, while non-REM sleep aids in physical recovery. Sleep deprivation impairs cognitive function and learning ability.\r\n\r\nhow to make the most of how your brain works\r\nTo optimize learning, maintain a routine that includes regular exercise, breaks, eight hours of sleep each night, and daily and weekly review of lecture content.\r\n",
